IN THE LATE 1940S CUSTODIANS OFTEN LIVED IN THE LIBRARIES THEY TENDED
RICHARD WAS OFFERED A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN IN A LIBRARY AND MOVED HIS WIFE AND SON RONALD, WHO HAD PREVIOUSLY THOUGHT THEM TO BE RICH IN
INITIALLY HIS SON WAS EMBARRASSED ABOUT HIS NON TRADITION HOME, BUT HE QUICKLY GREW TO SEE ITS ADVANTAGES
HE HAD MORE BOOKS THAN ALL THE CHILDREN OF HIS SCHOOL
HE DEVELOPED A HABIT OF READING LATE INTO THE NIGHT, NEEDING TO ONLY HEAD DOWNSTAIRS TO FIND THE ANSWERS TO HIS MANY QUESTIONS IN THE LIBRARIES ABUNDANCE OF BOOKS
HIS THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE GREW AND WAS LIFELONG
AS AN ADULT HE TALKED TO A GROUP CALLED STORY.
WHICH PRESENTED HIS RECOLLECTIONS IN AN INTERVIEW
HE WENT ON TO BECOME A PROFESSOR, THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO EVEN GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL

ALTHOUGH HIS FATHER WAS A QUIET MAN AND DID NOT MAKE MUCH COMMENT WHEN HE SHOWED HIM HIS NAME ON THE DOOR OF HIS VERY OWN OFFICE WITH THE TITLE OF PROFESSOR HE KNEW HOW MUCH HIS FATHER WANTED HIM TO SUCCEED IN LIFE
NO WORDS WERE REALLY NEEDED, HIS EYES SHOWN WITH PRIDE
RONALD CHERISHES HIS NON TRADITIONAL UPBRINGING IN THE LIBRARY AND CREDITS IT FOR EXPANDING HIS MIN
THIS STORY TOOK PLACE IN NEW YORK
THE STORY IS ABOUT A BLACK FAMILY
THE STORY WAS ILLUSTRATED WITH WELL DRAWN, COLORFUL AND RICH PICTURES
A YOUNG BOY DEVELOPS A LOVE OF LEARNING WHEN HIS FATHER GETS A JOB AS A JANITOR AT A LIBRARY
THE BOY IS ASHAMED AND NEVER BRINGS HIS FRIENDS OVER
HE EVENTUALLY REALIZES HOW LUCKY HE IS TO LIVE IN THE LIBRARY
